{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637621"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:44:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:44:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17672"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17672"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.24,0,0.52,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75875"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10386"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17672"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61388"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10487"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24308"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75875"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe glomerular filtration barrier in the kidney prevents the loss of important plasma proteins while allowing water and small solutes to pass freely into the urinary space.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary barrier to protein filtration in the glomerulus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fenestrated endothelial cells","Podocyte cell bodies","Mesangial cell matrix","Glomerular basement membrane","Bowman capsule epithelium"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglomerular basement membrane\u003C/strong\u003E is the barrier preventing protein filtration due to its negative charge and specific pore size. It contains type IV collagen and proteoglycans that create both a size and charge selective barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFenestrated endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E provide the first layer of filtration, but their pores are too large to effectively prevent protein passage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPodocyte cell bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are not the main functional unit maintaining the filtration barrier, but the foot processes and slit diaphragms instead.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesangial cell matrix\u003C/strong\u003E provides structural support but does not directly participate in filtration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBowman capsule epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the filtration barrier and only collects the filtered fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe three main components of the filtration barrier working together are the fenestrated endothelium, basement membrane, and podocyte foot processes with their slit diaphragms. The basement membrane provides the primary barrier through both size and charge selectivity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The glomerular filtration barrier consists of three layers: fenestrated endothelium, basement membrane, and podocyte foot processes.","The glomerular basement membrane contains negatively charged proteoglycans that repel plasma proteins.","Size selectivity of the glomerular barrier prevents filtration of molecules larger than albumin (66 kDa)."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61388"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17672"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61388"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T07:30:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T07:30:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10386"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75875"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":